It‚Äôs not called being in an authoritarian regime. It‚Äôs called being accountable for your advice. Same as being accountable in any consultation with a patient.

Trainees are encouraged to reflect on their practice. A habit that we are meant to continue for life. 

Time to reflect.

If you do decide to get on the megaphone and say things like ‚ÄúCOVID doesn‚Äôt spread in schools‚Äù particularly at a time when the CHO/CMO has closed schools due to the risk‚Ä¶ well‚Ä¶ you have to carry the responsibility for that statement.

Overall, if a doctor has concerns about a public health order, but the evidence base is not strong, or there is doubt, a private communication to the public health department is the way forward.

You don‚Äôt have to get on the megaphone straight away and say ‚Äúkids don‚Äôt get COVID‚Äù.

What about advocating for additional or evidence based protections? 

Complicated. I‚Äôll let someone else judge that one.

You‚Äôd think that it would be an easy answer, but it never is‚Ä¶

Yes. When one gives advice to the public, one does have to take into account the ‚Äúwhat if I‚Äôm wrong‚Äù question and ‚Äúwhat might happen in the future‚Äù‚Ä¶ 

People read something and then they walk away. They might never come back to Twitter to read anything again‚Ä¶

Now we have doctors arguing ‚Äúwhat is misinformation‚Äù in an attempt to confuse the issue. 

Well‚Ä¶ when there was little or no evidence, one decides to pipe up and say something against public health orders, and then it turns out to be wrong.

Measuring whether masks work in a population level was very tricky at the start of the pandemic, so all of the undermining was done based on basically no evidence or poor evidence. 

Undermining public health advice based on little or no evidence is a rotten thing to do.

It gets even harder when doctors decide to spread ‚Äúmisinformation‚Äù to *undermine public health advice*. 

Information poorly grounded in evidence, like ‚Äúmasks don‚Äôt work on a population level‚Äù.

Most public health education warns against playing with novel disease. There is also extensive coverage of the harms/side effects of some of the more intrusive public health measures (like stay at home orders). 

Dealing with a pandemic was never going to be easy.

Disease tends to cause damage. Major or minor. Novel disease is no exception and it was always likely there would be sequelae.

Chickens were always going to come home to roost.
Doctors that have spent the pandemic undermining the health protections recommended by CH/MO‚Äôs *publicly* place themselves and those they influence in a position of great risk.

But there are some that do speak out and broadly fall into two groups. 

Those that want added protections, and those that undermine the protections.
Average doctors rarely set out to undermine CH/MO‚Äôs on purpose. We understand that watching from the sidelines and being the one carrying the weight are two very different things.

There is a difference between the Chief Medical/Health Officer and the average doc on Twitter. 

Average doc on Twitter (including myself) does not carry the weight of responsibility for millions of lives. ->
